</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Identifying the presence of axillary node and internal mammary node metastases in patients with invasive breast cancer is critical for determining prognosis and for deciding on appropriate treatment. Sentinel lymph node biopsy (SLNB) is the definitive method to exclude axillary metastases. Patients with positive SLNB results generally undergo axillary lymph node dissection (ALND). The benefit of preoperative identification of axillary metastases is that it allows the surgeon to proceed directly to ALND and to avoid an unnecessary SLNB and the need for a second surgical procedure involving the axillary nodes. Knowledge of the important anatomic landmarks of the axilla is important in finding and accurately reporting suspicious lymph nodes. The pathologic features of nodal metastases illuminate the imaging appearances of these nodes, as depicted with all modalities. Ultrasonography (US) is the primary imaging modality for evaluating axillary nodes. Morphologic criteria, such as cortical thickening, hilar effacement, and nonhilar cortical blood flow, are more important than size criteria in the identification of metastases. US-guided lymph node sampling, especially with core biopsy, is invaluable in confirming the presence of a metastasis in a suspicious node. Core biopsy has been shown to be equal in safety to fine needle aspiration and has a significantly lower false-negative rate. Magnetic resonance imaging is also useful, with the added benefit of providing a global view of both axillae. Computed tomography and radionuclide imaging play a lesser role in imaging the axilla. Preoperative image-based identification and sampling of abnormal lymph nodes that have a high positive predictive value for metastases is an extremely important component in the management of patients with invasive breast cancer.</div><div role="paragraph">© RSNA, 2013</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.336125060">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.336125060">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig01" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig01.jpeg" height="1821" width="3000" aria-labelledby="fig01" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span> Possible algorithm for axillary staging in patients with early stage invasive breast cancer. The +/− indicates that in the setting of palpable lymph nodes, US evaluation and US-FNA or US-CNB may or may not be used.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig01">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig02" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig02.jpeg" height="1021" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig02" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span> Volume-rendered CT angiogram of the left axillary artery (red vessel) shows the boundaries of the three axillary levels (original CT image was altered to enhance the diagram). The origin of the pectoralis minor muscle is the coracoid process of the scapula. The margins of the area covered by the pectoralis minor muscle (approximate area outlined in black) define the axillary levels. One arterial branch originates on the inferior side of the axillary artery in level I: the subscapular artery. In this diagram, the artery bifurcates at the origin. It has a characteristic tortuosity (frequently a hook shape) and is a useful landmark. Note the first rib, which marks the junction of the subclavian artery and axillary artery, is the medial margin of the apex of the axilla, and therefore is the medial margin of level III.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig02">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig03a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig03a.jpeg" height="745" width="837" aria-labelledby="fig03a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span> CT anatomy of axillary level I. <b>(a)</b> Coronal CT angiogram of the axillary artery (white arrow) demonstrates the origin of the subscapular artery (black arrowhead) and its course, as it becomes the thoracodorsal artery (black arrow). Lymph nodes are found along its course (white arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Axial CT scan of the axilla (supine view) obtained for a non–breast-related complaint demonstrates the inferior aspect of level I. The thoracodorsal artery (white arrow) and accompanying vein are frequently seen as paired structures running along the posterolateral muscles. Small isolated segments of the circumflex scapular artery and its branches can be seen between the posterolateral muscles (black arrow). The lateral thoracic artery (black arrowhead) is seen running along the lateral border of the pectoralis minor muscle <i>(Pec. Min.)</i>. A small node is seen at the junction of levels I and II (white arrowhead). <i>Lat. dorsi</i> = latissimus dorsi, <i>Subscap</i> = subscapularis, <i>Ter. major</i> = teres major.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig03a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig03b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig03b.jpeg" height="745" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig03b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span> CT anatomy of axillary level I. <b>(a)</b> Coronal CT angiogram of the axillary artery (white arrow) demonstrates the origin of the subscapular artery (black arrowhead) and its course, as it becomes the thoracodorsal artery (black arrow). Lymph nodes are found along its course (white arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Axial CT scan of the axilla (supine view) obtained for a non–breast-related complaint demonstrates the inferior aspect of level I. The thoracodorsal artery (white arrow) and accompanying vein are frequently seen as paired structures running along the posterolateral muscles. Small isolated segments of the circumflex scapular artery and its branches can be seen between the posterolateral muscles (black arrow). The lateral thoracic artery (black arrowhead) is seen running along the lateral border of the pectoralis minor muscle <i>(Pec. Min.)</i>. A small node is seen at the junction of levels I and II (white arrowhead). <i>Lat. dorsi</i> = latissimus dorsi, <i>Subscap</i> = subscapularis, <i>Ter. major</i> = teres major.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig03b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig04a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig04a.jpeg" height="494" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig04a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span> US of the normal anatomy at the medial and lateral margins of axillary level I. <b>(a)</b> Transverse scan of the medial aspect of level I along the margin of the pectoralis muscles demonstrates the lateral thoracic artery (arrow) and a nearby normal level I lymph node (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Longitudinal scan of the lateral aspect of level I (arrow points to body site marker) demonstrates the longitudinal striations of the posterolateral muscles and a branch of the thoracodorsal artery (arrowhead). Nodes are frequently seen in this area.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig04a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig04b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig04b.jpeg" height="650" width="843" aria-labelledby="fig04b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span> US of the normal anatomy at the medial and lateral margins of axillary level I. <b>(a)</b> Transverse scan of the medial aspect of level I along the margin of the pectoralis muscles demonstrates the lateral thoracic artery (arrow) and a nearby normal level I lymph node (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Longitudinal scan of the lateral aspect of level I (arrow points to body site marker) demonstrates the longitudinal striations of the posterolateral muscles and a branch of the thoracodorsal artery (arrowhead). Nodes are frequently seen in this area.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig04b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig05" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig05.jpeg" height="650" width="832" aria-labelledby="fig05" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span> MR imaging of the normal left axilla in a high-risk screening patient, aged 46 years old. Level I nodes are usually seen in the central fat in isolation but occasionally can be traced to a particular artery. Axial high-resolution T1-weighted dynamic contrast material–enhanced (DCE) MR image (prone view) shows the lateral thoracic (white arrow) and thoracodorsal (black arrow) arteries, which could be traced back to their origins from the axillary artery and subscapular artery, respectively. Small branches (white arrowheads) of the lateral thoracic artery could be traced directly to the hilum of a normal level I lymph node (small white arrow), which is therefore a pectoral group node. <i>m</i>. = muscle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig05">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig06a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig06a.jpeg" height="742" width="840" aria-labelledby="fig06a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span> Level II lymph node in a patient with invasive ductal carcinoma and N1 nodal staging. Sagittal <b>(a)</b> and axial <b>(b)</b> non–fat-saturation T2-weighted images demonstrate an abnormal enlarged level II lymph node (arrow) in the fat behind the pectoralis minor muscle. If the nodes are not fixed or matted, and if there are three or fewer involved nodes, then even with level II involvement, the disease would still be characterized as N1.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig06a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig06b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig06b.jpeg" height="742" width="835" aria-labelledby="fig06b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span> Level II lymph node in a patient with invasive ductal carcinoma and N1 nodal staging. Sagittal <b>(a)</b> and axial <b>(b)</b> non–fat-saturation T2-weighted images demonstrate an abnormal enlarged level II lymph node (arrow) in the fat behind the pectoralis minor muscle. If the nodes are not fixed or matted, and if there are three or fewer involved nodes, then even with level II involvement, the disease would still be characterized as N1.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig06b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig07" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig07.jpeg" height="813" width="890" aria-labelledby="fig07" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7</span> Newly diagnosed invasive lobular cancer in a 75-year-old woman with a history of chronic lymphocytic leukemia of the ipsilateral breast. Radial-oriented US image of the right axilla demonstrates the longitudinally oriented striations of the pectoralis major and minor muscles (<i>m</i>.). Abnormal enlarged level II nodes (cursorss) are seen in the fat under the pectoralis minor. (Courtesy of Amy Johnson, MD, Department of Radiology, NorthShore University HealthSystem, Evanston, Ill.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig07">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig08" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig08.jpeg" height="813" width="785" aria-labelledby="fig08" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span> MR imaging of axillary levels I and II in a 56-year-old woman with invasive ductal carcinoma of the right breast. T1-weighted DCE MR image shows closely abutting level I and II axillary nodes. At ALND, the nodes were matted together, indicating N2 disease. The level II lymph node (arrow) is seen behind the enhancing pectoralis minor muscle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig08">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig09a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig09a.jpeg" height="587" width="948" aria-labelledby="fig09a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span> Abnormal Rotter space lymph node in a patient with ipsilateral invasive ductal carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal non–fat-saturation T2-weighted MR image demonstrates the index breast mass (*) and an enlarged node (arrow) in the fat between the pectoralis major and minor muscles. <b>(b)</b> Axial non–fat-saturation T2-weighted MR image shows the same enlarged Rotter space node (arrow). <i>pec</i>.= pectoralis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig09a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig09b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig09b.jpeg" height="587" width="927" aria-labelledby="fig09b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span> Abnormal Rotter space lymph node in a patient with ipsilateral invasive ductal carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal non–fat-saturation T2-weighted MR image demonstrates the index breast mass (*) and an enlarged node (arrow) in the fat between the pectoralis major and minor muscles. <b>(b)</b> Axial non–fat-saturation T2-weighted MR image shows the same enlarged Rotter space node (arrow). <i>pec</i>.= pectoralis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig09b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig10a.jpeg" height="494" width="861" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span> Innumerable enlarged, rounded nodes at all axillary levels, as well as a prominent supraclavicular node, in a patient who presented with palpable left axillary nodes but who was lost to follow-up. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT scan at the level of the supraclavicular fossa demonstrates a rounded prominent supraclavicular node (arrow). <b>(b)</b> On another view, level III nodes (arrow) medial to the pectoralis minor (*) and a level I node (arrowhead) lateral to the muscle are seen. <b>(c)</b> Coronal reformatted CT scan shows prominent nodes at all levels. The junction of the subclavian artery and axillary artery is at the first rib (arrow). This forms the medial margin of level III and the apex of the axilla. Supraclavicular nodes <i>(S)</i> are medial to the rib, and level III nodes <i>(III)</i> are lateral to the rib.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig10b.jpeg" height="494" width="814" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span> Innumerable enlarged, rounded nodes at all axillary levels, as well as a prominent supraclavicular node, in a patient who presented with palpable left axillary nodes but who was lost to follow-up. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT scan at the level of the supraclavicular fossa demonstrates a rounded prominent supraclavicular node (arrow). <b>(b)</b> On another view, level III nodes (arrow) medial to the pectoralis minor (*) and a level I node (arrowhead) lateral to the muscle are seen. <b>(c)</b> Coronal reformatted CT scan shows prominent nodes at all levels. The junction of the subclavian artery and axillary artery is at the first rib (arrow). This forms the medial margin of level III and the apex of the axilla. Supraclavicular nodes <i>(S)</i> are medial to the rib, and level III nodes <i>(III)</i> are lateral to the rib.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig10c.jpeg" height="775" width="850" aria-labelledby="fig10c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10c</span> Innumerable enlarged, rounded nodes at all axillary levels, as well as a prominent supraclavicular node, in a patient who presented with palpable left axillary nodes but who was lost to follow-up. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT scan at the level of the supraclavicular fossa demonstrates a rounded prominent supraclavicular node (arrow). <b>(b)</b> On another view, level III nodes (arrow) medial to the pectoralis minor (*) and a level I node (arrowhead) lateral to the muscle are seen. <b>(c)</b> Coronal reformatted CT scan shows prominent nodes at all levels. The junction of the subclavian artery and axillary artery is at the first rib (arrow). This forms the medial margin of level III and the apex of the axilla. Supraclavicular nodes <i>(S)</i> are medial to the rib, and level III nodes <i>(III)</i> are lateral to the rib.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig10c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig11a.jpeg" height="775" width="859" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span> Abnormal internal mammary lymph node in a patient with invasive ductal carcinoma in the left breast. <b>(a)</b> Axial maximum intensity projection view from a subtracted T1-weighted DCE MR imaging sequence demonstrates a large enhancing mass (arrow) in the lower inner quadrant of the left breast. An enlarged internal mammary lymph node (arrowhead) is evident but not well demonstrated. <b>(b)</b> Axial nonsubtracted T1-weighted DCE MR image shows an enlarged, diffusely enhancing internal mammary lymph node (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Gray-scale US image of the same node seen in <b>b</b> clearly shows the location of the node (arrow) between the parietal pleura/endothoracic fascia and the intercostal muscle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig11b.jpeg" height="775" width="816" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span> Abnormal internal mammary lymph node in a patient with invasive ductal carcinoma in the left breast. <b>(a)</b> Axial maximum intensity projection view from a subtracted T1-weighted DCE MR imaging sequence demonstrates a large enhancing mass (arrow) in the lower inner quadrant of the left breast. An enlarged internal mammary lymph node (arrowhead) is evident but not well demonstrated. <b>(b)</b> Axial nonsubtracted T1-weighted DCE MR image shows an enlarged, diffusely enhancing internal mammary lymph node (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Gray-scale US image of the same node seen in <b>b</b> clearly shows the location of the node (arrow) between the parietal pleura/endothoracic fascia and the intercostal muscle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig11c.jpeg" height="574" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig11c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11c</span> Abnormal internal mammary lymph node in a patient with invasive ductal carcinoma in the left breast. <b>(a)</b> Axial maximum intensity projection view from a subtracted T1-weighted DCE MR imaging sequence demonstrates a large enhancing mass (arrow) in the lower inner quadrant of the left breast. An enlarged internal mammary lymph node (arrowhead) is evident but not well demonstrated. <b>(b)</b> Axial nonsubtracted T1-weighted DCE MR image shows an enlarged, diffusely enhancing internal mammary lymph node (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Gray-scale US image of the same node seen in <b>b</b> clearly shows the location of the node (arrow) between the parietal pleura/endothoracic fascia and the intercostal muscle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig11c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig12.jpeg" height="1412" width="2300" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12</span> Schematic illustrates normal nodal architecture and the growth of metastatic disease. Metastases (in brown) enter the node through an afferent lymphatic and deposit in the subcapsular sinus. Early growth of the metastasis occurs at this location. Subsequent spread toward the medullary sinus often occurs in a heterogeneous pattern. The growing metastasis eventually coalesces and replaces normal nodal architecture. Extracapsular extension is also seen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig13.jpeg" height="675" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span> Subcapsular metastatic deposit. High-power photomicrograph (original magnification, ×100; hematoxylin-eosin stain) of a metastatic node shows a subcapsular micrometastatic deposit (white arrow). The nuclei are pale staining and gland formation can be seen. A sea of dark-staining lymphoid cells is seen in the uninvolved portion of the node (yellow *). The pink-staining node capsule (white *) and perinodal fat (black arrows) are also demonstrated. (Courtesy of Robert A. Goldschmidt, MD, Department of Pathology, NorthShore University Health System, Evanston, Ill.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig14.jpeg" height="675" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14</span> Heterogeneous spread. High-power photomicrograph (original magnification, ×100; hematoxylin-eosin stain) shows normal lymphoid cells and metastatic cells mixed in a heterogeneous fashion. At the top, pale-staining metastatic cells predominate (yellow *), and at the bottom right of the figure, there are confluent dark-staining residual lymphoid cells (white *). Between the two extremes (within the circle), most of the node appears as a heterogeneous mix of the two cell types. (Courtesy of Robert A. Goldschmidt, MD, Department of Pathology, NorthShore University Health System, Evanston, Ill.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig15a.jpeg" height="703" width="937" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span> Newly detected invasive ductal carcinoma in an 85-year-old woman with a palpable mass in the left breast. <b>(a)</b> Axillary US image shows an abnormally lobulated and hypoechoic lymph node with loss of the echogenic hilum. US-guided core biopsy revealed metastatic breast cancer. The patient subsequently underwent lumpectomy and ALND. <b>(b)</b> Low-power photomicrograph (original magnification, ×20; hematoxylin-eosin stain) of the explanted node demonstrates a large homogeneous area of metastatic cells (*) replacing the normal nodal architecture. A small amount of residual nodal tissue is seen in the upper left corner (arrowhead). The tract of the core biopsy needle can be appreciated in the lower right corner of the image (arrow). The ability of the metastasis to efface nodal architecture can be reflected in imaging with findings such as loss of the fatty hilum and the appearance of a diffusely hypoechoic node at US. <b>(c)</b> High-power photomicrograph (original magnification, ×40; hematoxylin-eosin stain) of an extranodal metastatic deposit with an associated tumor vessel (arrow) shows the pink-staining capsule of the node on the left (arrowheads), which separates the intranodal metastasis from the extranodal spread. (<a href="#fig15b">Fig 15b</a> and <a href="#fig15c">15c</a> courtesy of James Padgett, MD, Department of Pathology, NorthShore University HealthSystem, Evanston, Ill.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig15b.jpeg" height="703" width="937" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span> Newly detected invasive ductal carcinoma in an 85-year-old woman with a palpable mass in the left breast. <b>(a)</b> Axillary US image shows an abnormally lobulated and hypoechoic lymph node with loss of the echogenic hilum. US-guided core biopsy revealed metastatic breast cancer. The patient subsequently underwent lumpectomy and ALND. <b>(b)</b> Low-power photomicrograph (original magnification, ×20; hematoxylin-eosin stain) of the explanted node demonstrates a large homogeneous area of metastatic cells (*) replacing the normal nodal architecture. A small amount of residual nodal tissue is seen in the upper left corner (arrowhead). The tract of the core biopsy needle can be appreciated in the lower right corner of the image (arrow). The ability of the metastasis to efface nodal architecture can be reflected in imaging with findings such as loss of the fatty hilum and the appearance of a diffusely hypoechoic node at US. <b>(c)</b> High-power photomicrograph (original magnification, ×40; hematoxylin-eosin stain) of an extranodal metastatic deposit with an associated tumor vessel (arrow) shows the pink-staining capsule of the node on the left (arrowheads), which separates the intranodal metastasis from the extranodal spread. (<a href="#fig15b">Fig 15b</a> and <a href="#fig15c">15c</a> courtesy of James Padgett, MD, Department of Pathology, NorthShore University HealthSystem, Evanston, Ill.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig15c.jpeg" height="704" width="938" aria-labelledby="fig15c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15c</span> Newly detected invasive ductal carcinoma in an 85-year-old woman with a palpable mass in the left breast. <b>(a)</b> Axillary US image shows an abnormally lobulated and hypoechoic lymph node with loss of the echogenic hilum. US-guided core biopsy revealed metastatic breast cancer. The patient subsequently underwent lumpectomy and ALND. <b>(b)</b> Low-power photomicrograph (original magnification, ×20; hematoxylin-eosin stain) of the explanted node demonstrates a large homogeneous area of metastatic cells (*) replacing the normal nodal architecture. A small amount of residual nodal tissue is seen in the upper left corner (arrowhead). The tract of the core biopsy needle can be appreciated in the lower right corner of the image (arrow). The ability of the metastasis to efface nodal architecture can be reflected in imaging with findings such as loss of the fatty hilum and the appearance of a diffusely hypoechoic node at US. <b>(c)</b> High-power photomicrograph (original magnification, ×40; hematoxylin-eosin stain) of an extranodal metastatic deposit with an associated tumor vessel (arrow) shows the pink-staining capsule of the node on the left (arrowheads), which separates the intranodal metastasis from the extranodal spread. (<a href="#fig15b">Fig 15b</a> and <a href="#fig15c">15c</a> courtesy of James Padgett, MD, Department of Pathology, NorthShore University HealthSystem, Evanston, Ill.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig15c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig16.jpeg" height="487" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig16" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16</span> Normal level I lymph node. Gray-scale US image of a node shows its thin, hypoechoic cortex and smooth well-defined outline (+). The majority of the node is composed of the echogenic fatty hilum (*). The numbers <i>1</i> and <i>2</i> identify the long axis and short axis of the lymph node, respectively<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig16">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig17a.jpeg" height="674" width="897" aria-labelledby="fig17a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span> Invasive ductal carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image depicts a node with a distinct focal cortical bulge that involves the lower pole (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Color Doppler image demonstrates flow in the hilum (arrowhead) as well as cortical NHBF to the focal bulge (arrow). The combination of findings in this case was suspicious for metastatic disease, an interpretation that was confirmed with US-CNB.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig17a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig17b.jpeg" height="674" width="979" aria-labelledby="fig17b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span> Invasive ductal carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image depicts a node with a distinct focal cortical bulge that involves the lower pole (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Color Doppler image demonstrates flow in the hilum (arrowhead) as well as cortical NHBF to the focal bulge (arrow). The combination of findings in this case was suspicious for metastatic disease, an interpretation that was confirmed with US-CNB.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig17b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig18a.jpeg" height="576" width="952" aria-labelledby="fig18a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span> Invasive ductal carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image shows a node (cursors) with mild eccentric cortical thickening involving the lower pole (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Color Doppler image demonstrates flow in the hilum, as well as prominent flow adjacent to the cortex, with a small vessel entering the cortex (arrow), indicative of NHBF. The findings in this case were borderline suspicious, and US-CNB revealed metastatic disease.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig18a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig18b.jpeg" height="576" width="923" aria-labelledby="fig18b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span> Invasive ductal carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image shows a node (cursors) with mild eccentric cortical thickening involving the lower pole (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Color Doppler image demonstrates flow in the hilum, as well as prominent flow adjacent to the cortex, with a small vessel entering the cortex (arrow), indicative of NHBF. The findings in this case were borderline suspicious, and US-CNB revealed metastatic disease.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig19a.jpeg" height="1193" width="743" aria-labelledby="fig19a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span> Invasive ductal carcinoma in a patient with a large palpable mass and mammographically visible nodes. <b>(a)</b> Left mediolateral oblique view demonstrates the index mass (arrowhead) and at least one large round node (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Gray-scale US images of the axilla show multiple enlarged rounded homogeneously hypoechoic nodes (arrows) with loss of hilar fat. <b>(c)</b> Color Doppler images demonstrate nonhilar cortical flow in at least one of the nodes (black arrow) and diffuse hyperemia in another node (white arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig19b.jpeg" height="561" width="1132" aria-labelledby="fig19b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span> Invasive ductal carcinoma in a patient with a large palpable mass and mammographically visible nodes. <b>(a)</b> Left mediolateral oblique view demonstrates the index mass (arrowhead) and at least one large round node (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Gray-scale US images of the axilla show multiple enlarged rounded homogeneously hypoechoic nodes (arrows) with loss of hilar fat. <b>(c)</b> Color Doppler images demonstrate nonhilar cortical flow in at least one of the nodes (black arrow) and diffuse hyperemia in another node (white arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig19c.jpeg" height="557" width="1132" aria-labelledby="fig19c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19c</span> Invasive ductal carcinoma in a patient with a large palpable mass and mammographically visible nodes. <b>(a)</b> Left mediolateral oblique view demonstrates the index mass (arrowhead) and at least one large round node (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Gray-scale US images of the axilla show multiple enlarged rounded homogeneously hypoechoic nodes (arrows) with loss of hilar fat. <b>(c)</b> Color Doppler images demonstrate nonhilar cortical flow in at least one of the nodes (black arrow) and diffuse hyperemia in another node (white arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig19c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig20a.jpeg" height="552" width="984" aria-labelledby="fig20a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20a</span> Invasive ductal carcinoma in a 71-year-old woman with a palpable left breast mass that contained mammographically visible microcalcifications. <b>(a)</b> Axillary gray-scale US image demonstrates an abnormal node with the lower pole replaced by an irregular ill-defined hypoechoic mass (+). An echogenic calcification is seen in the mass (arrow). The number <i>1</i> indicates the long axis of the lymph node, and the number <i>2</i> indicates the margins of the hypoechoic mass. <b>(b)</b> Color Doppler US image reveals NHBF (arrow) in the mass. Core biopsy revealed metastatic invasive ductal carcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig20a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig20b.jpeg" height="552" width="891" aria-labelledby="fig20b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20b</span> Invasive ductal carcinoma in a 71-year-old woman with a palpable left breast mass that contained mammographically visible microcalcifications. <b>(a)</b> Axillary gray-scale US image demonstrates an abnormal node with the lower pole replaced by an irregular ill-defined hypoechoic mass (+). An echogenic calcification is seen in the mass (arrow). The number <i>1</i> indicates the long axis of the lymph node, and the number <i>2</i> indicates the margins of the hypoechoic mass. <b>(b)</b> Color Doppler US image reveals NHBF (arrow) in the mass. Core biopsy revealed metastatic invasive ductal carcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig20b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig21a.jpeg" height="786" width="792" aria-labelledby="fig21a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21a</span> Microcalcifications in a metastatic lymph node. <b>(a)</b> Mediolateral oblique view of the right breast demonstrates extensive pleomorphic calcifications (circle). Stereotactic biopsy revealed invasive ductal carcinoma and associated ductal carcinoma in situ. <b>(b)</b> Gray-scale US image of the right axilla demonstrates an abnormal lymph node with irregular focal cortical bulges and echogenic calcifications (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig21a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig21b.jpeg" height="786" width="883" aria-labelledby="fig21b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21b</span> Microcalcifications in a metastatic lymph node. <b>(a)</b> Mediolateral oblique view of the right breast demonstrates extensive pleomorphic calcifications (circle). Stereotactic biopsy revealed invasive ductal carcinoma and associated ductal carcinoma in situ. <b>(b)</b> Gray-scale US image of the right axilla demonstrates an abnormal lymph node with irregular focal cortical bulges and echogenic calcifications (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig21b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig22a.jpeg" height="566" width="1250" aria-labelledby="fig22a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22a</span> Appropriate Doppler settings. <b>(a)</b> Color Doppler US image of the axilla obtained with standard Doppler settings (arrows) in a patient with a T4N1 invasive ductal carcinoma demonstrates a mildly suspicious node with diffuse cortical thickening. Normal hilar flow is seen (circle). <b>(b)</b> However, on a color Doppler image obtained with a lower wall filter <i>(WF)</i> setting and a faster pulse repetition frequency <i>(PRF)</i> setting (arrows), distinct nonhilar cortical flow to the lower pole cortex is evident (arrowhead). Subsequent core biopsy directed toward the lower pole revealed metastasis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig22a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig22b.jpeg" height="616" width="1250" aria-labelledby="fig22b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22b</span> Appropriate Doppler settings. <b>(a)</b> Color Doppler US image of the axilla obtained with standard Doppler settings (arrows) in a patient with a T4N1 invasive ductal carcinoma demonstrates a mildly suspicious node with diffuse cortical thickening. Normal hilar flow is seen (circle). <b>(b)</b> However, on a color Doppler image obtained with a lower wall filter <i>(WF)</i> setting and a faster pulse repetition frequency <i>(PRF)</i> setting (arrows), distinct nonhilar cortical flow to the lower pole cortex is evident (arrowhead). Subsequent core biopsy directed toward the lower pole revealed metastasis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig22b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig23a.jpeg" height="740" width="847" aria-labelledby="fig23a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23a</span> US-CNB performed for a round and hypoechoic lymph node, with complete effacement of the fatty hilum, an appearance with a high likelihood of metastasis. US-CNB uses a core biopsy needle in which the stylet can be advanced manually before sampling. The needle is advanced to the node and then is cocked to expose the sample trough. <b>(a)</b> US image shows the needle, which is advanced through the node with the stylet extended and the sample trough visible (arrows) so that the tip can be positioned under US observation and vessels can be avoided. <b>(b)</b> As a subsequent image shows, the needle is then fired and the cannula advances over the stylet, but the tip of the stylet doesn’t move (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig23a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig23b.jpeg" height="740" width="828" aria-labelledby="fig23b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23b</span> US-CNB performed for a round and hypoechoic lymph node, with complete effacement of the fatty hilum, an appearance with a high likelihood of metastasis. US-CNB uses a core biopsy needle in which the stylet can be advanced manually before sampling. The needle is advanced to the node and then is cocked to expose the sample trough. <b>(a)</b> US image shows the needle, which is advanced through the node with the stylet extended and the sample trough visible (arrows) so that the tip can be positioned under US observation and vessels can be avoided. <b>(b)</b> As a subsequent image shows, the needle is then fired and the cannula advances over the stylet, but the tip of the stylet doesn’t move (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig23b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig24.jpeg" height="684" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig24" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24</span> Invasive ductal carcinoma and axillary node metastases. Axial T2-weighted MR image demonstrates an abnormal, lobulated axillary node with irregular and angulated margins (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig24">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig25a.jpeg" height="990" width="599" aria-labelledby="fig25a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25a</span> T1aN1a breast cancer in a 76-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Mediolateral oblique view shows a new abnormal lymph node (arrow), and results of US-FNA confirmed metastatic breast cancer. The site of the primary tumor was not evident at mammography. <b>(b)</b> Axial maximum intensity projection image from a subtracted T1-weighted DCE MR imaging sequence demonstrates the known abnormal node (arrow), as well as a suspicious microlobulated enhancing retroareolar mass (arrowhead). Results of subsequent biopsy showed that the retroareolar mass was the primary lesion. Note that the node appears enlarged and rounded and enhances diffusely. <b>(c)</b> On a nonsubtracted axial T1-weighted DCE MR image, the node enhances more intensely at its periphery (arrow). <b>(d)</b> Axial inversion recovery image shows diffuse increased signal intensity in the node (arrow). Background anatomic structures have minimal signal, and nodes are very conspicuous on inversion recovery images.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig25a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig25b.jpeg" height="990" width="726" aria-labelledby="fig25b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25b</span> T1aN1a breast cancer in a 76-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Mediolateral oblique view shows a new abnormal lymph node (arrow), and results of US-FNA confirmed metastatic breast cancer. The site of the primary tumor was not evident at mammography. <b>(b)</b> Axial maximum intensity projection image from a subtracted T1-weighted DCE MR imaging sequence demonstrates the known abnormal node (arrow), as well as a suspicious microlobulated enhancing retroareolar mass (arrowhead). Results of subsequent biopsy showed that the retroareolar mass was the primary lesion. Note that the node appears enlarged and rounded and enhances diffusely. <b>(c)</b> On a nonsubtracted axial T1-weighted DCE MR image, the node enhances more intensely at its periphery (arrow). <b>(d)</b> Axial inversion recovery image shows diffuse increased signal intensity in the node (arrow). Background anatomic structures have minimal signal, and nodes are very conspicuous on inversion recovery images.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig25b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig25c.jpeg" height="471" width="839" aria-labelledby="fig25c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25c</span> T1aN1a breast cancer in a 76-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Mediolateral oblique view shows a new abnormal lymph node (arrow), and results of US-FNA confirmed metastatic breast cancer. The site of the primary tumor was not evident at mammography. <b>(b)</b> Axial maximum intensity projection image from a subtracted T1-weighted DCE MR imaging sequence demonstrates the known abnormal node (arrow), as well as a suspicious microlobulated enhancing retroareolar mass (arrowhead). Results of subsequent biopsy showed that the retroareolar mass was the primary lesion. Note that the node appears enlarged and rounded and enhances diffusely. <b>(c)</b> On a nonsubtracted axial T1-weighted DCE MR image, the node enhances more intensely at its periphery (arrow). <b>(d)</b> Axial inversion recovery image shows diffuse increased signal intensity in the node (arrow). Background anatomic structures have minimal signal, and nodes are very conspicuous on inversion recovery images.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig25c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig25d.jpeg" height="471" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig25d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25d</span> T1aN1a breast cancer in a 76-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Mediolateral oblique view shows a new abnormal lymph node (arrow), and results of US-FNA confirmed metastatic breast cancer. The site of the primary tumor was not evident at mammography. <b>(b)</b> Axial maximum intensity projection image from a subtracted T1-weighted DCE MR imaging sequence demonstrates the known abnormal node (arrow), as well as a suspicious microlobulated enhancing retroareolar mass (arrowhead). Results of subsequent biopsy showed that the retroareolar mass was the primary lesion. Note that the node appears enlarged and rounded and enhances diffusely. <b>(c)</b> On a nonsubtracted axial T1-weighted DCE MR image, the node enhances more intensely at its periphery (arrow). <b>(d)</b> Axial inversion recovery image shows diffuse increased signal intensity in the node (arrow). Background anatomic structures have minimal signal, and nodes are very conspicuous on inversion recovery images.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig25d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig26" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig26.jpeg" height="780" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig26" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 26</span> Invasive ductal carcinoma. Axial T1-weighted DCE MR image of the right breast demonstrates invasive ductal carcinoma (arrowhead) and an abnormal right axillary node (arrow). The node displays heterogeneous enhancement and an irregular, slightly angulated margin.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig26">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig27a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig27a.jpeg" height="639" width="883" aria-labelledby="fig27a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 27a</span> Stage IV breast cancer with N3 axillary nodal staging and hepatic metastases in a patient who presented with a large palpable breast mass. <b>(a)</b> Subtracted sagittal T1-weighted DCE MR image demonstrates a large breast mass (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image obtained at the level of the axilla demonstrates matted level I nodes (arrow), findings that indicate at least N2 disease. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image obtained at a higher level demonstrates an enlarged rounded level III node (arrow), which would raise the nodal staging to N3 and therefore indicate stage IIIc disease. <b>(d)</b> Axial CT image of the liver demonstrates multiple hepatic metastases (arrows), findings that raise the disease stage from IIIc to IV.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig27a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig27b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig27b.jpeg" height="639" width="792" aria-labelledby="fig27b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 27b</span> Stage IV breast cancer with N3 axillary nodal staging and hepatic metastases in a patient who presented with a large palpable breast mass. <b>(a)</b> Subtracted sagittal T1-weighted DCE MR image demonstrates a large breast mass (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image obtained at the level of the axilla demonstrates matted level I nodes (arrow), findings that indicate at least N2 disease. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image obtained at a higher level demonstrates an enlarged rounded level III node (arrow), which would raise the nodal staging to N3 and therefore indicate stage IIIc disease. <b>(d)</b> Axial CT image of the liver demonstrates multiple hepatic metastases (arrows), findings that raise the disease stage from IIIc to IV.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig27b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig27c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig27c.jpeg" height="670" width="821" aria-labelledby="fig27c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 27c</span> Stage IV breast cancer with N3 axillary nodal staging and hepatic metastases in a patient who presented with a large palpable breast mass. <b>(a)</b> Subtracted sagittal T1-weighted DCE MR image demonstrates a large breast mass (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image obtained at the level of the axilla demonstrates matted level I nodes (arrow), findings that indicate at least N2 disease. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image obtained at a higher level demonstrates an enlarged rounded level III node (arrow), which would raise the nodal staging to N3 and therefore indicate stage IIIc disease. <b>(d)</b> Axial CT image of the liver demonstrates multiple hepatic metastases (arrows), findings that raise the disease stage from IIIc to IV.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig27c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig27d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig27d.jpeg" height="672" width="854" aria-labelledby="fig27d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 27d</span> Stage IV breast cancer with N3 axillary nodal staging and hepatic metastases in a patient who presented with a large palpable breast mass. <b>(a)</b> Subtracted sagittal T1-weighted DCE MR image demonstrates a large breast mass (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image obtained at the level of the axilla demonstrates matted level I nodes (arrow), findings that indicate at least N2 disease. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image obtained at a higher level demonstrates an enlarged rounded level III node (arrow), which would raise the nodal staging to N3 and therefore indicate stage IIIc disease. <b>(d)</b> Axial CT image of the liver demonstrates multiple hepatic metastases (arrows), findings that raise the disease stage from IIIc to IV.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig27d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig28a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig28a.jpeg" height="711" width="754" aria-labelledby="fig28a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 28a</span> Two synchronous masses of invasive ductal carcinoma in the left breast of a 54-year-old patient with 19 nodes removed at ALND, two of which were positive. <b>(a)</b> Axial maximum intensity projection image from subtracted T1-weighted DCE MR imaging demonstrates two large enhancing masses (arrowheads) and an enlarged axillary node (arrow). The presence of involved axillary nodes indicates stage IIb disease. <b>(b)</b> Axial high-resolution T1-weighted DCE MR image also reveals an enlarged internal mammary lymph node (arrow). Metastases to the internal mammary lymph node chain in the presence of axillary metastases are considered N3; thus, the disease stage was changed to stage IIIC. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal T1-weighted DCE MR image demonstrates the enlarged enhancing left internal mammary lymph node (arrow), which is located in the intercostal space. Internal mammary lymph nodes are sandwiched between the intercostal muscles and ribs superficially and the endothoracic fascia and parietal pleura more deeply. The node is confined to the intercostal spaces because the endothoracic fascia is tightly adherent to the deep surface of the ribs (<a href="#r15" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r15">15</a>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig28a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig28b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig28b.jpeg" height="711" width="921" aria-labelledby="fig28b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 28b</span> Two synchronous masses of invasive ductal carcinoma in the left breast of a 54-year-old patient with 19 nodes removed at ALND, two of which were positive. <b>(a)</b> Axial maximum intensity projection image from subtracted T1-weighted DCE MR imaging demonstrates two large enhancing masses (arrowheads) and an enlarged axillary node (arrow). The presence of involved axillary nodes indicates stage IIb disease. <b>(b)</b> Axial high-resolution T1-weighted DCE MR image also reveals an enlarged internal mammary lymph node (arrow). Metastases to the internal mammary lymph node chain in the presence of axillary metastases are considered N3; thus, the disease stage was changed to stage IIIC. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal T1-weighted DCE MR image demonstrates the enlarged enhancing left internal mammary lymph node (arrow), which is located in the intercostal space. Internal mammary lymph nodes are sandwiched between the intercostal muscles and ribs superficially and the endothoracic fascia and parietal pleura more deeply. The node is confined to the intercostal spaces because the endothoracic fascia is tightly adherent to the deep surface of the ribs (<a href="#r15" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r15">15</a>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig28b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig28c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.336125060/asset/images/large/125060fig28c.jpeg" height="1108" width="700" aria-labelledby="fig28c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 28c</span> Two synchronous masses of invasive ductal carcinoma in the left breast of a 54-year-old patient with 19 nodes removed at ALND, two of which were positive. <b>(a)</b> Axial maximum intensity projection image from subtracted T1-weighted DCE MR imaging demonstrates two large enhancing masses (arrowheads) and an enlarged axillary node (arrow). The presence of involved axillary nodes indicates stage IIb disease. <b>(b)</b> Axial high-resolution T1-weighted DCE MR image also reveals an enlarged internal mammary lymph node (arrow). Metastases to the internal mammary lymph node chain in the presence of axillary metastases are considered N3; thus, the disease stage was changed to stage IIIC. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal T1-weighted DCE MR image demonstrates the enlarged enhancing left internal mammary lymph node (arrow), which is located in the intercostal space. Internal mammary lymph nodes are sandwiched between the intercostal muscles and ribs superficially and the endothoracic fascia and parietal pleura more deeply. The node is confined to the intercostal spaces because the endothoracic fascia is tightly adherent to the deep surface of the ribs (<a href="#r15" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r15">15</a>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.336125060&amp;id=fig28c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div